06553nam a22009855i 9780812205725DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013941230  a(OCoLC)979756380  a97808122057257 a10.9783/97808122057252doi  a(DE-B1597)449472  a(OCoLC)847550599  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aE185.61.A437 2012eb 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a323.1196/0731 aAlexander, Shawn Leigh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut13aAn Army of Lions :bThe Civil Rights Struggle Before the NAACP /cShawn Leigh Alexander. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b22 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPolitics and Culture in Modern America00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Aceldama and the Black Response -- tChapter 2. “Stand Their Ground on Th is Civil Rights Business” -- tChapter 3. Interregnum and Resurrection -- tChapter 4. Not Just “A Bubble in Soap Water” -- tChapter 5. To Awaken the Conscience of America -- tChapter 6. Invasion of the Tuskegee Machine -- tChapter 7. An Army of Mice or an Army of Lions? -- tChapter 8. “It Is Strike Now or Never” -- tEpilogue -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn January 1890, journalist T. Thomas Fortune stood before a delegation of African American activists in Chicago and declared, "We know our rights and have the courage to defend them," as together they formed the Afro-American League, the nation's first national civil rights organization. Over the next two decades, Fortune and his fellow activists organized, agitated, and, in the process, created the foundation for the modern civil rights movement.An Army of Lions: The Civil Rights Struggle Before the NAACP traces the history of this first generation of activists and the organizations they formed to give the most comprehensive account of black America's struggle for civil rights from the end of Reconstruction to the formation of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People in 1909. Here a host of leaders neglected by posterity—Bishop Alexander Walters, Mary Church Terrell, Jesse Lawson, Lewis G. Jordan, Kelly Miller, George H. White, Frederick McGhee, Archibald Grimké—worked alongside the more familiar figures of Ida B. Wells-Barnett, W. E. B. Du Bois, and Booker T. Washington, who are viewed through a fresh lens.As Jim Crow curtailed modes of political protest and legal redress, members of the Afro-American League and the organizations that formed in its wake—including the Afro-American Council, the Niagara Movement, the Constitution League, and the Committee of Twelve—used propaganda, moral suasion, boycotts, lobbying, electoral office, and the courts, as well as the call for self-defense, to end disfranchisement, segregation, and racial violence. In the process, the League and the organizations it spawned provided the ideological and strategic blueprint of the NAACP and the struggle for civil rights in the twentieth century, demonstrating that there was significant and effective agitation during "the age of accommodation."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryx19th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryx20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy19th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitics and governmentx19th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitics and governmentx20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitics and governmenty19th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitics and governm